article.headline: New Mexico 95, Mississippi 42
article.story: ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- New Mexico emptied its bench and none of the starters played more than 22 minutes, but the points just kept coming. Mark Walters scored 15 of his 17 points in the first half and New Mexico used a pair of early scoring runs to beat Mississippi 95-42 at the Jim Thorpe Classic on Saturday night. This one was over early as New Mexico (2-0) used an 18-2 run to take a 31-13 lead, then closed out the first half with a 13-0 run for a 44-15 lead that kept growing through the second half, no matter what combination of players the Lobos used. "Ole Miss isn't that bad and we're not that good," New Mexico coach Ritchie McKay said. "We want to be humble in victory." Mississippi coach Rod Barnes talked to his players for more than an hour after the game. When he emerged from the locker room, he said his young team -- with only one senior -- couldn't handle the pressure of playing a hot-shooting New Mexico team in The Pit. "We didn't respond well and we didn't defend them," Barnes said. "On those runs they got some great looks and we had some breakdowns. They put us away early." Mississippi (1-1) trailed 13-11 with 11:00 left in the first half when New Mexico reserve guard Jeff Hart hit a 3-pointer to start the 18-2 run. Walters scored seven points and David Chiotti had four in the run. The Rebels' only points in that stretch was a tip-in by Trey Hampton. It was Ole Miss' only field goal in the final 11 minutes of the first half. "It was caused by our defensive effort," McKay said. The loss was the worst for Mississippi since 1991, when the Rebels lost to Georgia 117-62. It also tied for the fifth worst loss in school history. "We were helping each other out and when we're doing that, we're out there having fun," Walters said. "Up and down the court, everybody getting touches. You're locking up (on defense) and the bench is into it. That's when you're playing your best basketball and that's what we did tonight." Ole Miss hit just 14 of 55 shots (25.5 percent) and was 4-of-24 on 3-pointers. The Rebels had no one in double figures, with Bam Doyne and Mike Smith the team's high scorers with 7 points each. New Mexico also dominated the rebounding by a margin of 50-24. New Mexico hit 14 of 27 3s, with five players hitting at least two 3-pointers. Walters had a trio of 3s, all in the first half. Walk-on Blake Harden and Chad Toppert each scored 11 points for New Mexico and Anthony Teague scored 10 in just seven minutes. It's the first time Teague has gotten any playing time, including the two exhibition games. Twelve of the 14 New Mexico players who got into the game scored.
